"Oerlemans J.","Quantifying global warming from the retreat of glaciers",1994,"Science","264","5156",,"243","245",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0028183967&partnerID=40&md5=6d91252cd4e0cc5f27116b843e169f3b","Inst. for Mar. and Atmosph. Research, Utrecht University, Princetonplein 5, 3584 CC Utrecht, Netherlands","Oerlemans, J., Inst. for Mar. and Atmosph. Research, Utrecht University, Princetonplein 5, 3584 CC Utrecht, Netherlands","Records of glacier fluctuations compiled by the World Glacier Monitoring Service can be used to derive an independent estimate of global warming during the last 100 years. Records of different glaciers are made comparable by a two-step scaling procedure: one allowing for differences in glacier geometry, the other for differences in climate sensitivity. The retreat of glaciers during the last 100 years appears to be coherent over the globe. On the basis of modeling of the climate sensitivity of glaciers, the observed glacier retreat can be explained by a linear warming trend of 0.66 kelvin per century.",,"glacier; global warming; linear warming trend; retreat; sensitivity",,,,,,"Nye, J.F., (1960) Proc. R. Soc. London, 256, p. 559; Hoinkes, H., Steinacker, R., (1975) Riv. Ital. Geofis. Sci. Affini, 1, p. 97; Kuhn, M., (1981) Int. Assoc. Hydrol. Sci. Publ., 131, p. 3; Oerlemans, J., (1986) Nature, 320, p. 430; Budd, W.F., Jenssen, D., (1975) Int. Assoc. Hydrol. Sci. Publ., 131, p. 257; Kühn, M., (1985) Z. Gletscherkd Glazialgeol., 21, p. 409; (1967) Fluctuations of Glaciers, 1-5. , Unesco, Paris; Björnsson, H., (1979) Jokull, 29, p. 74; Björnsson, H., (1988) Hydrology of Ice Caps in Volcanic Regions, , University of Iceland, Reykjavik; Bogen, J., Wold, B., Østrem, G., (1989) Glacier Fluctuations and Climatic Change, pp. 109-128. , J. Oerlemans, Ed. Kluwer, Dordrecht, Netherlands; Hastenrath, S., (1984) The Glaciers of Equatorial East Africa, , Kluwer, Dordrecht, Netherlands, chap. 6; noteFurbish, D.J., Andrews, J.T.,